# 63_app_version_smoke — third headless-verb singleton from ARC m5b
# (s263 m2). Opens the third slot in the Tier 4 row: 2/~4-5 -> 3/~4-5.
# Sibling smoke to 44 (proj save) and 49 (export svg) in singleton-
# open shape — third session in the m5b arc where the numerator on a
# tier row ticks up rather than verbs accumulating on an existing
# singleton.
#
# `app` is the process-scope identity singleton — one registry entry
# per app session, no per-instance proxy. m2 ships one verb (`version`)
# reading the CURVZ_VERSION macro plumbed via CMake's
# target_compile_definitions from project(curvz VERSION 0.9.0). m3
# adds the second pure-read verb `gtk_version` on the same singleton;
# this smoke covers `version` only — smoke 64 covers `gtk_version`.
#
# ── What this smoke exercises ─────────────────────────────────────────────
#
# `app version` has a one-case contract (see AppScriptable.hpp for the
# full design block):
#
#   Branch A (happy path):  always. Returns the build version string
#                           via ScriptValue::text wrapping the
#                           CURVZ_VERSION macro expansion.
#   Branch B (extra args):  any positional argument is a misuse.
#                           Refuses with "app version: expected zero
#                           arguments".
#
# Unlike proj save's three refusal branches and export svg's five, app
# version has no refusal branches in Branch A — the macro is always
# defined by the build (the Scriptable has a #ifndef fallback to
# "unknown" so the file always compiles, but a healthy build defines
# the macro and the smoke asserts the expected value). No project-
# state interrogation; no path-safety pre-flight; no canvas drag
# check. The verb is the simplest possible Scriptable invocation.
#
# This smoke runs Branch A (operator-visual on the ok+value echo, plus
# an equality assertion against the expected build version), plus the
# argument-count refusal (Branch B), plus an unknown-verb refusal on
# the same singleton. Three observable lines, one assertion.
#
# ── Caller context ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────
#
# This smoke runs through ScripterWindow's listener, m_context =
# RunContext::Scripter (set in ScripterWindow's ctor, see s244 m2
# wiring). `app version` declares its mask as Scripter | TestRunner
# (Macro is OUT — recorded macros replaying a version-read on a
# different build produce stale recorded values, violating the
# recorded-macro mental model). So Scripter is allowed; the
# dispatcher's gating check passes and the verb body runs.
#
# Tenth consumer of Scriptable::context_mask() in the codebase
# (Inspector + 5 proj verbs + 2 export verbs + this one). Registry-
# promotion clock at 10/n, still held by design.
#
# ── Test isolation ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────
#
# `app version` is a pure read with no side effects. Idempotent across
# repeated calls; no on-disk effect; no in-memory state mutation; no
# observable difference between first call and Nth call. Safest smoke
# in the singleton-open corpus.
#
# ── Predicted observables ─────────────────────────────────────────────────
#
# Expected summary line at smoke close:
#
#   4 lines, 1 pass, 0 fail, 2 error
#
# - 1 "ok" line from `app version` happy-path call (Phase 1).
# - 1 PASS from the assertion (Phase 2).
# - 1 "error" line from extra-args refusal (Phase 3).
# - 1 "error" line from unknown-verb refusal (Phase 4).
#
# Same conservative-smoke shape as smoke 60 (1-verb, 2-refusal) plus
# one assertion swapped in for the property-only read. Sibling shape
# to smoke 44 (proj save) at 5 lines / 2 pass / 0 fail / 0 error —
# this smoke has fewer assertions (1 vs 2) because there's no
# precondition to assert (the build version is what it is; we just
# check the value matches expectation) and two refusal lines instead
# of zero (a singleton-open smoke validates the dispatcher's refusal
# paths alongside the happy path, which the smoke 44 didn't because
# proj's refusals had their own dedicated smokes 45-48).

#[sub] === Phase 1: app version (Branch A — happy path) ===

#[sub] Call the verb. The expected trace line is:
#[sub]
#[sub]   > app version
#[sub]   ok "0.9.0"
#[sub]
#[sub] Operator-visual on the `ok` echo and the echoed string value.
#[sub] CURVZ_VERSION is plumbed via target_compile_definitions in
#[sub] CMakeLists.txt from project(curvz VERSION 0.9.0); the macro
#[sub] expansion is a string literal that the Scriptable wraps in
#[sub] ScriptValue::text. If the CMake build dropped the version
#[sub] propagation (target_compile_definitions line removed), the
#[sub] Scriptable's defensive #ifndef fallback returns "unknown" and
#[sub] the Phase 2 assertion fails — observable in the trace, not a
#[sub] silent regression.

app version

#[sub] === Phase 2: assert the version is the expected build number ===

#[sub] The DSL's assert is equality-only on query results, but the
#[sub] verb-form `app version` produces the same value path as a
#[sub] property would; the listener evaluates the invocation,
#[sub] captures the return, and compares against the literal. If
#[sub] CMake's project(curvz VERSION) bumps in a future session,
#[sub] update this assertion to the new value alongside the bump
#[sub] (CMake is the source of truth; the smoke follows it).

assert app version == "0.9.0"

#[sub] === Phase 3: extra-args refusal (Branch B) ===

#[sub] Pass a positional argument the verb doesn't accept. The
#[sub] expected trace line is:
#[sub]
#[sub]   > app version "extra"
#[sub]   error invoke threw: app version: expected zero arguments
#[sub]
#[sub] Operator-visual on the error message; the listener's
#[sub] runtime_error catch surfaces the Scriptable's throw message
#[sub] verbatim. Same shape as proj save_as's empty-path refusal
#[sub] and export svg's wrong-args refusal — std::runtime_error
#[sub] thrown by the Scriptable, caught by the dispatcher,
#[sub] formatted as `error invoke threw: <message>`.

app version "extra"

#[sub] === Phase 4: unknown-verb refusal on the same singleton ===

#[sub] Address the singleton with a verb name that doesn't exist
#[sub] (`info` is a common natural-language probe; if a future
#[sub] milestone adds `app info`, change this smoke's unknown-verb
#[sub] string to something else still-not-defined). The expected
#[sub] trace line is:
#[sub]
#[sub]   > app info
#[sub]   error invoke threw: app: unknown verb 'info'
#[sub]
#[sub] Operator-visual on the unknown-verb message. Validates the
#[sub] singleton's invoke-dispatch fall-through correctly identifies
#[sub] unrecognised verbs rather than silently returning Null (which
#[sub] would mask typos in user scripts).

app info

#[sub] === Predicted observables ────────────────────────────────────────────

#[sub] Expected summary line:
#[sub]
#[sub]   4 lines, 1 pass, 0 fail, 2 error
#[sub]
#[sub] Third singleton-open in the Tier 4 row (after proj at s246 m1
#[sub] and export at s251 m1); Tier 4 ticks 2 → 3. Tenth consumer of
#[sub] context_mask() in the corpus; registry-promotion clock at 10/n,
#[sub] still held by design.
